          'Lithium-ion batteries are not one chemistry — they are a family of electrochemistries sharing the lithium-ion intercalation mechanism but differing critically in safety, energy density, cycle life, temperature tolerance, and cost. Understanding the trade-offs between the two dominant stationary/motive chemistries is essential for a battery technician operating across UPS, BESS, EV, and telecom applications. LITHIUM IRON PHOSPHATE (LFP — LiFePO₄): the safest lithium chemistry for stationary applications. LFP cells have very stable crystal structures that resist thermal runaway — the oxygen in the cathode is covalently bonded to phosphorus and is not easily released even under abuse (overcharge, external heat, physical damage). Trade-offs: lower energy density (~90–160 Wh/kg) than NMC, and a very flat discharge voltage curve (3.2–3.3V nominal) that makes charge-state estimation by voltage nearly impossible without a BMS. LFP\'s advantages: exceptional cycle life (2,000–6,000+ cycles to 80% capacity), wide temperature tolerance, and the thermal stability that makes it the first choice for stationary BESS, UPS systems, and increasingly telecom standby.',
          'NICKEL MANGANESE COBALT (NMC — LiNi₁₋ₓ₋ᵧMnₓCoyO₂): higher energy density (150–250 Wh/kg) and higher operating voltage (3.6–3.7V nominal) than LFP, making NMC the dominant chemistry for EV traction batteries and portable devices where energy density is the primary constraint. The trade-off is reduced thermal stability — NMC cathodes can release oxygen when overheated or overcharged, enabling exothermic reactions and fire. NMC batteries require more sophisticated BMS protection than LFP and have more conservative thermal management requirements. BATTERY TECHNICIAN RULE: assume every lithium system requires BMS-governed charging; never charge a lithium cell with a lead-acid charger or any charger not specified for the chemistry and pack configuration. LITHIUM POLYMER (LiPo) is a form factor (pouch cells with gel electrolyte) not a chemistry — LiPo cells may contain NMC or LFP chemistry.',
