          'The BATTERY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM (BMS) is simultaneously the safety system, the metering system, the state estimator, and the communications interface of every lithium battery pack. A BMS failure in a lithium system is never a minor event — without BMS protection, a single cell can exceed its voltage limit, its temperature limit, or its current limit without any cutoff, progressing to thermal runaway. BMS CORE FUNCTIONS: (1) CELL-LEVEL VOLTAGE MONITORING — measures every cell in the pack individually; trips the pack off if any cell reaches the over-voltage (OVP) or under-voltage (UVP) threshold. (2) CELL BALANCING — corrects charge imbalances between cells using passive balancing (bleeding energy from high cells as heat) or active balancing (transferring energy from high cells to low cells). (3) CURRENT PROTECTION — trips the pack on over-current (OCP) in discharge and over-charge-current conditions; the maximum continuous and peak discharge rates are BMS-enforced limits. (4) TEMPERATURE MANAGEMENT — monitors cell and module temperatures; inhibits charging below 0°C (lithium plating risk) and above 45°C, and inhibits discharge above 60°C (chemistry-dependent); triggers cooling or heating as needed. (5) STATE ESTIMATION — calculates and reports state of charge (SOC, %), state of health (SOH, %), and estimated remaining runtime or energy. (6) COMMUNICATION — reports all monitored parameters to the inverter, charger, or building management system via CAN bus, Modbus, RS-485, or BACnet.',
